Package au.edu.anu.omhtk.rng

Class Pcg32

java.lang.Object
java.util.Random
au.edu.anu.omhtk.rng.Pcg32
All Implemented Interfaces:
Serializable
public class Pcg32 extends Random

Implementation of a permuted congruential generator (PCG). This family of pseudo-random number generators includes some that are "simultaneously extremely fast, extremely statistically good, and extremely space efficient" (O'Neill, 2014). Here, we use the PCG32 algorithm.

  • PCG algorithm is used; in particular, this is a port of the minimal C implementation.
  • Instances of Pcg32 are not thread-safe and so it doesn't obey the Random contract.
Author:
Ian Davies - Dec 6, 2018

      public int nextInt()
      Overrides:
      nextInt in class Random
      Returns:
      the next pseudo-random, approximately uniformly distributed int value from this random number generator's sequence. The general contract of nextInt is that one int value is pseudo-randomly generated and returned. All 2^32 possible int values are produced with (approximately) equal probability.

    • seed

      public void seed​(long initState, long initSeq)
      Initializes the generator with a long as the state and a long stream number. The latter must be unique to ensure that multiple generators with the same seed will have different sequences.
      Parameters:
      initState - an initial state
      initSeq - an initial stream

    • seed

      public void seed()
      Initializes the generator with current time as the state and a (very likely to be) unique stream number. This ensures that even if multiple generators are initialized using this method while System.nanoTime() returns the same time, they will have different sequences.
